  "text": "There was, however, increased interest in the possible opiate involvement of renal function. Administration of opiate agonists produced conflicting results, although much of the inconsistency could be accounted for by the kind of receptor being stimulated. The u agonists morphine [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] or a metabolite of it, morphine-6-glucuronide (M6G) (238), reduced urine output, although morphine-3-glucuronide (M3G) increased it [CITATION_3] . Naloxone reversed the effect of all three, but it was thought that the action of M3G was not through opiate receptors because it is not found to bind to any receptors [CITATION_4] . Dermorphin, another u agonist, given ICV but not IV, produced the opposite effect, increasing urine flow, and the u antagonist ¢3-funaltrexamine blocked the effect. Dermorphin, however, had no effect on ef-fective renal plasma flow or glomerular-filtration rats and increased efferent renal sympathetic nerve activity, so that the action was not mediated by central changes in renal outflow to the kidneys or hemodynamics [CITATION_5] . Activation of different subtypes might be responsible for the differences.",
